# Create a bash script for taking websites backup.
They have a static website running on App-Server 3 in the Datacenter, and the bash script should be named 'beta_backup.sh'
(Also remember to place the script under /scripts directory on App Server 3)

     #!/bin/bash

# create a timestamp for the backup file
timestamp=$(date +%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S)

# create a zip archive of the beta directory
cd /var/www/html/
zip -r xfusioncorp_beta_${timestamp}.zip beta

# save the archive in /backup/
mv xfusioncorp_beta_${timestamp}.zip /backup/

# copy the archive to Nautilus Backup Server using scp
scp -o "StrictHostKeyChecking no" /backup/xfusioncorp_beta_${timestamp}.zip \
    nautilus@<backup_server_ip>:/backup/

# make sure the archive is readable by the server user
chmod 644 /backup/xfusioncorp_beta_${timestamp}.zip

NB:
Note that you will need to replace <backup_server_ip> with the actual IP address or hostname of the backup server.
Also, make sure to save the script under the /scripts directory on App Server 3, and to make it executable using chmod +x beta_backup.sh.

//Alternative:

      #!/bin/bash

# Create a timestamp for the filename
timestamp=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")

# Create the zip archive
cd /var/www/html
zip -r xfusioncorp_beta_$timestamp.zip beta

# Save the archive on App Server 3
mkdir -p /backup
cp xfusioncorp_beta_$timestamp.zip /backup

# Copy the archive to Nautilus Backup Server
sshpass -p 'your_password_here' scp xfusioncorp_beta_$timestamp.zip username@nautilus-backup-server:/backup/

# Clean up the archive on App Server 3
rm xfusioncorp_beta_$timestamp.zip

NB:
To use this script, save it as /scripts/beta_backup.sh on App Server 3 and make it executable using the command chmod +x beta_backup.sh.
You will need to replace your_password_here with the password for the Nautilus Backup Server user account, and username with the actual username of the user account.
You can also modify the file paths if necessary.
